==={{anchor|In manga and anime|Ninja themed manga and anime series}}Anime and manga=== {{for2|ninja anime theatrical films and OVAs|[[List of ninja films#Japanese (anime)|List of ninja films]]}} [[File:Ninja Hattori-kun C76.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Four people in costume|''[[Ninja Hattori-kun]]'' cosplayers at [[Comiket]] 76]] The following [[manga]] and [[anime]] series feature ninjas: * {{Nihongo|''[[Akakage|Akakage, The Masked Ninja]]''|仮面の忍者赤影|Kamen no Ninja Akakage}}: Anime adaptation of the [[Akakage|television series]] * ''[[Anime Ganbare Goemon]]'': Anime based on the ''[[Goemon (series)|Goemon]]'' video-game series * ''[[Azumi (manga)|Azumi]]'': The title character is a young woman brought up as part of a team of assassins charged with killing warlords who were threatening the uneasy peace in feudal Japan after the [[Sengoku period]] * {{Nihongo|''[[Basilisk (manga)|Basilisk]]''|バジリスク〜甲賀忍法帖〜|Bajirisuku ~Kōga Ninpō Chō~|Basilisk: The Kōga Ninja Scrolls}}: Historical fantasy manga and anime where two ninja clans (Tsubagakure of the [[Iga-ryū|Iga]] and Manjidani of [[Kōga-ryū|Kouga]]) fight to determine which grandson of [[Tokugawa Ieyasu]] will become the next ''[[shōgun]]''. It features many characters from rival ninja clans during the [[Tokugawa shogunate]]. * ''Black Lion (Kuro no Shishi)'': Manga series<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebookjapan.jp/ebj/title/5192.html |title=黒の獅士 - 電子書籍・コミックはeBookJapan |publisher=Ebookjapan.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-06-10}}</ref> and anime film adaptation<ref>{{cite web|url=http://animeworld.com/reviews/blacklion.html|title=Black Lion : Anime Reviews : AAW|publisher=Animeworld.com|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> * ''Brave10'': Manga adaptation of ''Sanada Ten Braves''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://brave10.com/ |title=アニメ「BRAVE10」公式サイト |publisher=Brave10.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Change 123]]'' * {{Nihongo|''[[Flame of Recca]]''|烈火の炎|Rekka no Honō}}: A teenage boy learns that he is a descendant of a [[Hokage (Flame of Recca)|Hokage]] ninja clan which perished during the reign of [[Oda Nobunaga]]. * ''[[Fūma no Kojirō]]'' * ''[[Genki Bakuhatsu Ganbaruger]]'' * ''Henshin Ninja Arashi'': Manga by [[Shotaro Ishinomori]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vintageninja.net/?tag=arashi |title=Vintage Ninja |publisher=Vintage Ninja |date= |accessdate=2012-11-14}}</ref> * {{Nihongo|''[[Himawari!]]''|ひまわりっ!}}: Comedy series about a non-ninja teacher at an all-girl ninja school * {{Nihongo|''I Am Sarutobi!''||Ore wa Sarutobi da!}}: Manga by [[Osamu Tezuka]] about [[Sarutobi Sasuke]]. * ''[[Igano Kabamaru]]'' * {{Nihongo|''[[Jubei-chan: The Ninja Girl]]''|十兵衛ちゃん|Jūbei-chan}}: Action-comedy television series about a teenage girl who turns into a deadly ninja warrior when she puts on an eye patch * ''[[Kage Gari|Shadow Hunters (Kage Gari)]]'' * ''[[Kage Kara Mamoru!]]'': A teenage boy transforms into a ninja to protect his neighbor. * ''[[Kagetora]]'' * {{Nihongo|''[[Kamui the Ninja|Kamui the Ninja: Stories Other Than the Legend]]''|忍風カムイ外伝|Ninpū Kamui Gaiden}}: 1969 anime adaptation of ''The Legend of Kamui'' * ''Kunoichi Hajimemashita!'': Gag manga series<ref>{{cite web|author=はころく 作 |url=http://rookie.shonenjump.com/series/2FR0RT0AC8I |title=くノ一はじめました！ - 少年ジャンプルーキー |publisher=Rookie.shonenjump.com |date= |accessdate=2015-11-06}}</ref> * ''Kunoichi Mahouden'': Erotic manga series<ref>{{cite web|url=http://item.rakuten.co.jp/hyakumu/10003344/|title=ڳŷԾۡۤΰ6仳/硧̡Ź ɴ̴ ŷԾŹ|work=ŷԾ|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> * ''[[Karasu Tengu Kabuto]]'': Manga series adapted into an anime series and an OVA film * ''The Last Kunoichi (Kunoichi Bakumatsu Kitan)'': Erotic anime series about [[kunoichi]] caught in the struggles of the late Tokugawa shogunate<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mania.com/last-kunoichi-vol-1_article_78710.html |title=Last Kunoichi Vol. #1 |publisher=Mania.com |date= |accessdate=2012-11-14}}</ref> * ''[[The Legend of Kamui]]'': Manga series * ''[[Kyatto Ninden Teyandee]]'' (''[[Samurai Pizza Cats]]''): In the Japanese version, the title characters are ninja facing ninja enemies. * ''[[Lupin III]]'': [[Goemon Ishikawa XIII]], a member of Lupin's gang, is the 13th descendant of the [[Ishikawa Goemon|historical Goemon]]. * ''[[Mushibugyo]]'' [[File:Sai cosplay.jpg|thumb|alt=Young person in costume, holding a scroll and artist's brush|[[Cosplay]] of the ''[[Naruto]]'' character Sai]] * ''[[Nabari no Ou]]'': A modern-day Japanese student holds the most powerful secret art in the ninja world. * {{Nihongo|''[[Manga Sarutobi Sasuke|Ninja, the Wonder Boy]]''|まんが猿飛佐助|Manga Sarutobi Sasuke}}: Adventures of young ninja [[Sarutobi Sasuke]] * {{Nihongo|''[[Ninja Girls]]''|乱飛乱外|Rappi Rangai|lit. Flying out of turbulence}}: A boy rescues a ''kunoichi'', who becomes his servant and introduces him to her friends. * {{Nihongo|''[[Ninja Hattori-kun]]''|忍者ハットリくん}} * {{Nihongo|''[[Ninja Nonsense|Ninja Nonsense: The Legend of Shinobu]]''|ニニンがシノブ伝|Ninin ga Shinobuden|also ''2x2 Shinobuden''}}: A teenage girl becomes involved with a ''kunoichi'' and her family. * {{Nihongo|''[[Ninja Senshi Tobikage|Ninja Robots]]''|忍者戦士飛影|Ninja Senshi Tobikage|lit. "Ninja Warrior Tobikage"}}: Science-fiction series in which Martian teenagers pilot ninja-style robots to protect a princess in an interplanetary war * {{Nihongo|''[[Ninja Scroll: The Series]]''||Jūbē Ninpūchō Ryūhōgyoku Hen}} * ''[[Path of the Assassin|Path of the Assassin (Hanzō no Mon)]]'': Story of ninja [[Hattori Hanzō]] * ''[[Rakudai Ninja Rantarō]]'' * ''[[Nintama Rantarō|Rantaro the Ninja Boy (Nintama Rantarō)]]'': Anime series for young children about Rantarou, his friends and teachers at a ninja school * ''[[Samurai Legend]] (Kaze no Sho)'': Historical manga by [[Jiro Taniguchi]] * ''Sarutobi Sasuke'': Manga by [[Shigeru Sugiura]]<ref name=ss>{{cite web|url=http://www.kyotomm.jp/HP/international/english/2009/02/sugiur101th_e.php|title=Kyoto International Manga Museum|publisher=Kyotomm.jp|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> * ''Sasuga no Sarutobi'': TV series and comedy manga by [[Fujihiko Hosono]] about a ninja high school<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sokuyomi.jp/product/sasuganosa_001/CO/1|title=さすがの猿飛 1巻【電子書籍のソク読み】豊富な無料試し読み|work=ソク読み|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.jp/%E3%81%95%E3%81%99%E3%81%8C%E3%81%AE%E7%8C%BF%E9%A3%9BDVD-BOX-%E4%B8%89%E3%83%84%E7%9F%A2%E9%9B%84%E4%BA%8C/dp/B0000DJWRL|title=さすがの猿飛DVD-BOX|publisher=Amazon.co.jp|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.jp/%E3%81%95%E3%81%99%E3%81%8C%E3%81%AE%E7%8C%BF%E9%A3%9B-1-MF%E6%96%87%E5%BA%AB-%E7%B4%B0%E9%87%8E-%E4%B8%8D%E4%BA%8C%E5%BD%A6/dp/4840108242|title=Amazon.co.jp： さすがの猿飛 (1) (MF文庫): 細野 不二彦: 本|publisher=Amazon.co.jp|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> * ''[[Science Ninja Team Gatchaman|Science Ninja Team Gatchaman (Kagaku Ninja Tai Gatchaman)]]'': Five young International Science Organization operatives, dressed like birds and trained in the ninja arts * ''[[Senran Kagura]]'': Anime version of the video game * ''[[Shinobu Kokoro: Hidden Heart]]'' * ''[[Shinobi Life]]'' * ''Shinobi no Kuni'', based on a novel by Wada Ryou. * ''Shōnen Jiraiya'': manga by Shigeru Sugiura<ref name=ss/> * ''[[Shōnen Ninja Kaze no Fujimaru]]'' * ''[[Tail of the Moon|Tail of the Moon (Tsuki no Shippo)]]'': A young ninja-in-training seeks to marry in order to bear a child for the sake of her family. * ''[[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles: Legend of the Supermutants]]'': Anime version of ''Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles'' * ''Tenshi wa Maiorita - Kunoichi Ibun'': Historical manga series by [[Ryoichi Ikegami]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ne.jp/asahi/ocl/irdb/ir10_SakuhinData/section7/151003-SD_TensihaMaiorita-ALL.pdf |format=PDF |title=Database |publisher=Ne.jp |accessdate=2015-11-06}}</ref> * ''[[The Yagyu Ninja Scrolls|The Yagyu Ninja Scrolls (Y+M)]]'': Historical fantasy manga series by ''Basilisk'' author Segawa Masaki * ''Zannen Kunoichi Den'': manga series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://comic-meteor.jp/zannen/|title=残念くのいち伝 - 日本最大級の無料Webコミック[COMICメテオ]|publisher=Comic-meteor.jp|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> * ''Zanpei Kumotori'': manga by [[Takao Saito]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vintageninja.net/?p=1109 |title=Vintage Ninja |publisher=Vintage Ninja |date= |accessdate=2012-11-14}}</ref>
[[Sanpei Shirato]] has written ninja-themed manga, including ''Akame&nbsp;– The Red Eyes'',{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} {{Nihongo|''Band of Ninja''||Ninja Bugeicho}} (later adapted into an anime film),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vintageninja.net/?tag=ninja-bugeicho |title=Vintage Ninja |publisher=Vintage Ninja |date= |accessdate=2012-11-14}}</ref> ''Kaze no Ishimaru'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vintageninja.net/?p=204 |title=Visionary character design |publisher=Vintage Ninja |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> ''Ninpou Hiwa'', ''Ookami Kozou'', ''Ninja Senpuu'', ''[[The Legend of Kamui]]'' and ''Watari'' (later adapted into the live-action film ''Watari, the Ninja Boy'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vintageninja.net/?p=3538 |title=Vintage Ninja |publisher=Vintage Ninja |date=2012-07-31 |accessdate=2012-11-14}}</ref>
The following stories contain a ninja character, but are not ninja-themed: {{div col}} * ''[[Afro Samurai]]'': One of Afro's personalities is [[List of Afro Samurai characters#Ninja Ninja|Ninja Ninja]]. * ''Ai Kora'': [[Ai Kora#Kirino Ootori|Kirino Ootori]] comes from a ninja family, and supporting characters [[Ai Kora#Ai Hagidzuka|Ai Hagidzuka]] and [[Ai Kora#Kunoichi Awayuki|Kunoichi Awayuki]] practice ninjutsu. * ''[[Angel Blade]]'': Hentai (adult) [[Original video animation|OVA]] series * ''[[Bastard!!]]'': Ninja Master Gara * ''[[Blade of the Immortal]]'': Master Sōri and his female students, Meguro and Tanpopo, in the final story arcs * ''[[Chōdenji Machine Voltes V]]'': [[Chōdenji Machine Voltes V#The Voltes Team and Allies|Megumi Oka]], the only female member of the Voltes V Team, is a ninja. * ''[[Demon King Daimao]]'': Female characters are involved with the rival Koga and Iga ninja clans. * ''[[Dragon Ball (franchise)|Dragon Ball]]'': Anthropomorphic ninja dog [[Emperor Pilaf|Shu]] and the six Murasaki brothers * ''Erotic Torture Chamber'': Hentai anime OVA series * ''[[Fatal Fury: The Motion Picture]]'' and ''[[Fatal Fury 2: The New Battle]]'': Two anime films based on the video-game series with the ninja [[Mai Shiranui]] * ''[[Gin Tama]]''; Sarutobi Ayame, Jiraia's and Tsukuyo's Hyakka team and the Shinobi Five (Hattori Zenzou, Gou, Shuwa, Wakikaoru and Matsuo) * ''[[Ginga: Nagareboshi Gin]]'', ''[[Ginga Legend Weed]]'' and ''Kacchū no Senshi Gamu''. * ''Hakodate Youjin Buraichou Himegami'' * ''[[Haō Taikei Ryū Knight]]'' * ''[[Inuyasha]]'' * ''[[Is This a Zombie?]]'': [[Is This a Zombie?#Seraphim|Seraphim]] is a vampire ninja who lives with the main character. * ''[[Kanokon]]'': Ren and Ai * ''[[Kaze ga Gotoku]]'' * ''[[Kenichi: The Mightiest Disciple]]'': [[List of Shijō Saikyō no Deshi Kenichi characters#Shigure Kousaka|Shigure Kousaka]] is a weapons master who uses ninja weapons. * ''[[Kōtarō Makaritōru!]]'' * ''[[Labyrinth of Flames|Labyrinth of Flames (Honoo no Labyrinth)]]'' * ''[[Millennium Actress]]''<ref>{{cite web|last=Tobias |first=Scott |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/millennium-actress,27341/ |title=Millennium Actress &#124; Film &#124; The New Cult Canon |publisher=The A.V. Club |date=2009-04-30 |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Mirmo!|Mirmo! (Wagamama Fearī Mirumo de Pon!)]]'': Yashichi, Yamane and Nezumi * ''[[Musashi Gundoh]]'' * ''[[Nagasarete Airantou]]'': Several of the island girls practice ninjutsu. * ''[[Negima!: Magister Negi Magi]]'': [[List of Negima characters#Kaede Nagase|Kaede Nagase]] practices ninjutsu. * ''[[Outlaw Star]]'': [["Twilight" Suzuka]] is a ninja assassin. * ''[[Pyu to Fuku! Jaguar]]'': Hammer, a bumbling ninja * ''[[Rurouni Kenshin]]'': Manga and TV series featuring the [[Oniwabanshu]] ninja group, which includes [[Shinomori Aoshi]] and [[Makimachi Misao]] * ''Sailor Victory'': Comedy OAV series about a team of policewomen using ninja robots<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mania.com/sailor-victory_article_73941.html |title=Sailor Victory |publisher=Mania.com |date= |accessdate=2012-11-14 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090718111356/http://www.mania.com/sailor-victory_article_73941.html |archivedate=2009-07-18 |df= }}</ref> * ''[[Samurai Deeper Kyo]]'': Sarutobi Sasuke, a member of [[Sanada Yukimura]]'s ninja group * ''[[Samurai Spirits]]'' * ''[[Short-Tempered Melancholic|Short-Tempered Melancholic (Kanshakudama no Yuutsu)]]'' * ''[[Soar High! Isami]]'' * ''[[Soul Eater (manga)|Soul Eater]]'': Students [[Black☆Star|Black Star]] and [[Tsubaki Nakatsukasa|Tsubaki]] practice ninjutsu. * ''[[Sgt. Frog|Sgt. Frog (Sergeant Keroro)]]'': Dororo and Koyuki are skilled in ninjutsu. * ''[[Transformers: The Headmasters]]'': [[Sixshot]] is portrayed as a ninja. * ''[[Tsubasa: Reservoir Chronicle]]'': [[Kurogane (Tsubasa: Reservoir Chronicle)|Kurogane]] is a ninja in the main group who travels to parallel worlds. {{div col end}}
Supporting ninja appearances include ''Ah! Itoshi no Banchousama'' (Hirayama Hayaka's ninja bodyguard), ''[[Bobobo-bo Bo-bobo]]'' (OVER's Ninja Assassin Corp and the Ultimate Five Assassins), ''[[Code Geass]]'' (Sayoko Shinozaki), ''[[Cutey Honey]]'', ''[[Dinosaur King]]'' (episode "Ninja Nightmare"),<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7uyTAAjI_l4| title = Dinosaur King: Ninja Nightmare&nbsp;– YouTube| format = YouTube| date = June 9, 2010| author = [[4Kids TV|4KidsTV]]}}</ref> ''[[F-Zero: GP Legend (anime)|F-Zero: GP Legend]]'' (Dream), ''[[Hero Tales]]'', ''[[Hunter x Hunter]]'' (Hanzo and Machi), ''[[Hyper Police]]'' (Kasumi), ''[[Kamen no Maid Guy]]'' (ninja maids Shizuku and Tsurara), ''[[King Arthur (TV series)|King Arthur]]'', ''[[Kinnikuman]]'' (the Ninja), ''[[Kirby: Right Back at Ya!]]'' ([[Kirby (character)|Kirby]] becomes a ninja and works with Benikage and Yamikage in the episode "[[List of Kirby: Right Back at Ya! episodes|Visiting Ninja, Benikage!]]"), ''Kotetsu no Daibouken'' (Kagari), ''[[Lone Wolf and Cub]]'', ''[[Machine Robo: Battle Hackers]]'', ''[[Magical Nyan Nyan Taruto]]'' (Rakugan), ''[[Magical Princess Minky Momo]]'' ("Ninja Arrived! Momo is Ninja"), ''[[Mega Man Star Force (anime)|Mega Man Star Force]]'' (the Tribe-On transformation Green Ninja), ''[[Metal Fighter Miku]]'' ("Pretty Four vs The Lady Ninjas"), ''[[Miami Guns]]'', ''[[My-HiME]]/[[My-Otome]]'' ([[Akira Okuzaki]]), ''[[Nagasarete Airantou]]'' (Mikoto), ''[[Oh My Goddess!]]'' ([[List of Oh My Goddess characters#The Three Ninjas|Marller's ninja trio]]), ''[[Planetes]]'' (Tanabe's neighbors in "[[List of Planetes episodes#ep06|The Lunar Flying Squirrels]]"),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mania.com/planetes-vol-2_article_78003.html |title=Planetes Vol. #2 |last=Morton | first = Bryan| publisher=Mania.com |date=January 3, 2006 |accessdate=2013-01-14}}</ref> the ''[[Pokémon (anime)|Pokémon]]'' series and ''[[Pokémon: The Electric Tale of Pikachu]]'' (Aya, Koga-Kyō and Janine-Anzu), ''PQ Angels'', ''Raimuiro Ryuukitan X'' (Kasuri Hattori), ''[[Ranma 1/2]]'' ([[Konatsu Kenzan|Konatsu]], [[Sasuke Sarugakure]], and [[List of Ranma ½ characters#Shirokuro|Shirokuro]]), ''[[Saber Marionette]]'', ''[[Sailor Moon]]'' (the villain of the week Oniwabandana<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soul-hunter.com/sailormoon/profiles/villains/motd/oniwabandana.php|title=the oracle :: Oniwabandana|publisher=Soul-hunter.com|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref>), ''[[Sakura Wars]]'', ''[[Samurai Champloo]]'' ("Bogus Booty" and "Baseball Blues"), ''[[Samurai Girl: Real Bout High School]]'', ''[[Sengoku Collection]]'' (Kotaro Fuuma), ''[[Sonic X]]'' (the E-91 Lady Ninja and Espio the Chameleon), ''[[Sorcerer Hunters]]'', ''[[The King of Braves GaoGaiGar|The King of Braves GaoGaiGar (Yūsha Ō GaoGaiGā)]]'' (Volfogg), ''[[Those Who Hunt Elves]]'', ''Tower of Etruria'' (Palmyra),<ref>{{cite web|last=Ross| first= Carloss | url=http://www.themanime.org/viewreview.php?id=913 |title=THEM Anime Reviews 4.0 - Tower of Etruria |publisher=Themanime.org |date= |accessdate=2013-01-14}}</ref> ''[[Ultraman]]'' ([[Alien Baltan]]), ''[[Yami to Bōshi to Hon no Tabibito]]'', ''[[Yakitate! Japan]]'' ("Nin Nin Nin!! My Way of Ninja!"), ''[[Yoshimune (anime)|Yoshimune]]'' (Kunoichi) and ''[[YuYu Hakusho]]'' ([[List of YuYu Hakusho characters#Team Shadow Channelers|Team Shadow Channelers]]).
===Armed groups=== Several paramilitary, police and militia groups use the names "Ninja" or "Ninjas": * The Santomean special-police force of the [[Democratic Republic of São Tomé and Príncipe]], officially known as the Emergency Police, are popularly known as Ninjas.<ref>{{Citation| last = Reuters AlertNet| first = | date = October 10, 2007| year = | title = Elite "Ninja" police free hostages in Sao Tome| publisher = Reuters| pages =| url = http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L1030667.htm| accessdate = August 26, 2009}}</ref> * Rebels in the [[Pool Region]] of the Republic of the Congo called themselves [[Ninja (militia)|Ninja]].<ref>{{Citation | last = Tsoumou | first = Christian | date = June 8, 2007 | year = | title = Congo's Ninja rebels burn weapons and pledge peace | publisher = Reuters| pages =| url = http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L08473674.htm | accessdate = August 26, 2009}}</ref> * The Red Berets, a [[Serbs of Croatia|Croatian Serb]] rebel paramilitary group of [[Dragan Vasiljković]] based in [[Knin]], Croatia, called themselves "Kninjas".<ref>{{Citation| last1 = Robinson | first1 = Natasha | last2 = Madden | first2 = James | date = April 13, 2007| year = | title = Captain Dragan set for extradition | publisher = ''[[The Australian]]'' | url = http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,20867,21548551-2702,00.html | accessdate = August 26, 2009}}</ref> During the early 1990s, the Kninjas were the subject of a [[Serbia]]n comic-book series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19911225&slug=1324914 |title=Serbian Media Bombard Public With Nazi Footage, 'Kninjas' |publisher=Community.seattletimes.nwsource.com |date=1991-12-25 |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/specials/the-real-captain-dragan/ |title=The Real Captain Dragan&nbsp;– ABC News |publisher=Abc.net.au |date=2011-05-27 |accessdate=2013-08-05}}</ref> * Although some death squads active during the [[Indonesian occupation of East Timor]] called themselves "Ninja", the name was apparently borrowed from film rather than the Japanese model.<ref>{{Citation | last = Lane | first = Max | date = March 1, 1995 | year = | title = 'Ninja' terror in East Timor | publisher = [[Green Left Weekly|Green Left Online]] | pages =| url = http://www.greenleft.org.au/1995/177/12558 | accessdate = August 26, 2009}}</ref> "Ninja" gangs were also active elsewhere in Indonesia.<ref>{{Citation | last = [[BBC News]] | first = | date = October 24, 1998 | year = | title = Indonesia's 'ninja' war | publisher = BBC News | pages =| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/200660.stm | accessdate = August 26, 2009}}</ref> * During the [[Algerian Civil War]], the government's commando units were known as "Ninja" because of their black hoods.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Ninjas Crack Down|author=Christopher Dickey|publisher=newsweek.com|year=1995|url=http://www.newsweek.com/1995/06/18/the-ninjas-crack-down.html|accessdate=2011-01-12}}</ref> * The FBI's Hostage Rescue Team have been nicknamed "Ninjas".<ref>''Waco&nbsp;– The Inside Story'', FRONTLINE, PBS 1995</ref>
==={{anchor|In film}}Film=== {{Main|List of ninja films}}
==={{anchor|In games}}Games=== ===={{anchor|In video games}}Video games==== {{main|List of ninja video games}} In addition to video games, several game-development companies use "ninja" in their name: [[Ninja Studio]], [[Ninja Theory]], Ninjaforce, NinjaKiwi,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ninjakiwi.com/ |title=Free Online Games |publisher=Ninja Kiwi |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> and [[Team Ninja]]. In [[massively multiplayer online role-playing game]]s (MMORPGs), "ninja", "loot ninja" or "ninja looter" pejoratively describes a player who has stolen something from another player.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cheatcc.com/extra/top10ninjasinvideogames.html |title=Top 10 Ninjas In Video Games - Cheat Code Central |publisher=Cheatcc.com |date= |accessdate=2015-06-05}}</ref>
===={{anchor|In traditional games}}Traditional games==== Ninja-themed [[role-playing game]]s (RPGs) include: * ''[[Bushido (role-playing game)|Bushido]]'': A role-playing game set in feudal Japan, it includes the supplement ''Ninja&nbsp;– Shadows Over Nippon''. * ''[[Choose Your Own Adventure]]'': There are ninja characters in several [[gamebook]]s in the series: ''Secret of the Ninja'' (#66), ''Return of the Ninja'' (#92), ''The Lost Ninja'' (#113), ''Ninja Cyborg'' (#155) and ''Ninja Avenger'' (#179). * ''[[Feng Shui (role-playing game)|Feng Shui]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlas-games.com/product_tables/AG4011.php |title=Iron & Silk&nbsp;– Atlas Games: Charting New Realms of Imagination |publisher=Atlas Games |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Hero System]]'': Includes the ''Ninja Hero'' gamebook. * ''[[Legend of the Five Rings]]'': Set in a world resembling feudal Japan, it includes the [[sourcebook]] ''Way of the Ninja''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.l5r.com/archive/rpg/products/archive.html |title=Legend of the Five Rings - Roleplaying Game - Products |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=2008-10-11 |accessdate=2016-08-12 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011220754/http://www.l5r.com/archive/rpg/products/archive.html |archivedate=2008-10-11 |df= }}</ref> * ''[[Dungeons & Dragons]]'': [[Ninja (Dungeons & Dragons)|Ninja]] is a [[character class]] first appearing in the 1985 first-edition supplement, ''[[Oriental Adventures]]''. ''Test of the Ninja'' is an ''AD&D'' gamebook. The Ninja class was added to edition 3.5 in ''[[Complete Adventurer]]''. * ''[[Ninja Burger]]'': Three editions and a card game based on the website * ''[[Ninjas and Superspies]]'': Modern setting * ''[[Queen's Blade]]'': Two series of erotic gamebooks featuring the ninja Shizuka and video-game ninja such as Mai Shiranui, [[Kasumi (Dead or Alive)|Kasumi]] and [[Taki (Soulcalibur)|Taki]] in ''[[Queen's Gate]]''. * ''[[Rifts (role-playing game)|Rifts]]'': The Mystic Ninja and Ninja Jucier character classes were introduced in the book, ''Rifts World Book 8: Japan''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://palladium-store.com/1001/product/818-Rifts-World-Book-8-Japan.html |title=Palladium Books Store Rifts® World Book 8: Japan |publisher=Palladium-store.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Street Fighter: The Storytelling Game]]'' * ''[[Sengoku (role-playing game)|Sengoku]]'': Samurai game set in 16th-century Japan which includes the sourcebook, ''Shinobi, Shadows of Nihon'' * ''[[Spycraft]]'': Modern espionage game with a ninja character class in the [[campaign setting]] ''World On Fire''<ref>{{cite web |author1=Alex Flagg |author2=Scott Gearin |author3=Patrick Kapera |url=http://www.crafty-games.com/node/81 |title=World on Fire |publisher=Crafty Games |date=2007-12-24 |accessdate=2013-08-04 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513035239/http://www.crafty-games.com/node/81 |archivedate=2014-05-13 |df= }}</ref> * ''[[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles & Other Strangeness]]'': Game by Palladium Books based on the Ninja Turtles * ''[[The Way of the Tiger]]'': Ninja-themed series of gamebooks, set in a fantasy world
Ninja ara also featured in [[collectible card game]]s such as ''[[Legend of the Five Rings (collectible card game)|Legend of the Five Rings CCG]]'', ''[[Magic: The Gathering]]'' (where the ability Ninjutsu was introduced in the set [[Betrayers of Kamigawa]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wizards.com/magic/displaythemedeck.asp?set=bok&decknum=2 |title=Betrayers of Kamigawa Theme Deck&nbsp;– Ninjutsu |publisher=Wizards.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref>) and ''[[Mortal Kombat Kard Game]]'', and in some [[miniature wargaming]] games, such as ''[[Heroscape]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.atomz.com/search/?sp_a=sp10028aa8&sp_t=heroscape&sp_k=Heroscape&sp_q=ninja|title=Heroscape - Search Results|publisher=Search.atomz.com|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref>
==={{anchor|On the Internet|Websites and web comics|Other}}Internet=== Ninja-themed websites include: * ''[[Ask A Ninja]]'': Series of podcasts where a ninja answers questions about ninja * ''Ikenhisu'': Live-action web series<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zeM7I3jEACY|title=Ikenhisu full episodes|work=YouTube|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> * ''[[Ninja Burger]]'': Humor website, RPG, card game and book in which ninja run a fast-food delivery service * ''[[Ninja Spirit (video series)|Ninja Spirit]]'': Series of short martial-arts parody videos * ''[[Ninjai|Ninjai: The Little Ninja]]'': Flash animation * ''[[Ninja the Mission Force]]'': Comedy series * ''[[No Need for Bushido]]'': Webcomic * ''One Warm Night'': Web TV series<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC7XHidh5IvBcLPHbhesC9uQ|title=One Warm Night - Original Series|work=YouTube|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> * ''[[Pucca]]'': Flash-animated Korean media franchise which includes a book and TV series * ''[[Real Ultimate Power]]'': Humour website created by Robert A. Hamburger, a 13-year-old character * ''[[The Adventures of Dr. McNinja]]'': Webcomic about an Irish doctor ninja obsessed with Batman * ''[[Snafu Comics#TIN The Incompetent Ninja|TIN The Incompetent Ninja]]'': Webcomic series * ''Vexika'': Live-action web series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vexika.com/|title=Vexika|publisher=Vexika.com|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> * ''[[White Ninja (webcomic)|White Ninja]]'': Webcomic part of the [[National Lampoon Inc|National Lampoon]] Humor Network * ''Zombies vs. Ninjas'': Web cartoon series by [[Shut Up! Cartoons]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL4D8DEC1191107AB8|title=Zombies vs. Ninjas|publisher=Youtube.com|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref>
In information technology, "cyber ninja" are sophisticated counter-hackers.<ref>{{cite news|last=Drew |first=Christopher |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/03/education/edlife/03cybersecurity.html |title=Cybersecurity&nbsp;– Wanted - 'Cyber Ninjas' |publisher=''[[The New York Times]]''|date=2009-12-29 |accessdate=2010-06-30}}</ref>
==={{anchor|In literature}}Literature=== ===={{anchor|In novels}}Novels==== Ninja-themed novels include: * ''[[American Chillers]]'' and [[Magic Tree House series|''Magic Tree House'' series]]: ''New York Ninjas''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanchillers.com/index.php/cybrary-launch-pages/84-american-chillers-cybrary/97-4-new-york-ninjas|title=#4 New York Ninjas|publisher=Americanchillers.com|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> and ''Night of the Ninjas'' * ''Brett Wallace: Ninja Master:'' Eight-book series by Wade Barker (Richard Meyers)<ref name=dw>{{cite web|url=http://vintageninja.net/?p=3234|title=Vintage Ninja|publisher=Vintageninja.net|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> * ''[[Demon King Daimao]]'': [[Light novel]]s by Shotaro Mizuki, with girls representing the rival Koga and Iga ninja clans; adapted into anime and manga series * ''[[The Diamond Chariot]]'': [[Erast Fandorin]] learns ninjutsu in Japan. * ''[[Fukurō no Shiro]]'' by [[Ryotaro Shiba]], who also wrote a collection of short stories (''Saigo no Igamono'') * ''[[Kage Kara Mamoru!]]:'' Series of light novels adapted into manga and anime series * ''[[The Kouga Ninja Scrolls|The Kouga Ninja Scrolls (Kōga Ninpōchō)]]'': Novel by [[Futaro Yamada]] about two rival ninja clans, the [[Iga-ryū|Iga]] and [[Kōga-ryū|Kouga]]; adapted into manga and anime series and a live-action film * ''Tulku, a Tale of Modern Ninja'': Novel by American ninjutsu practitioner [[Stephen K. Hayes]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Tulku_a_Tale_of_Modern_Ninja.html?id=pvefMQEACAAJ | title= Tulku, a tale of modern Ninja&nbsp;– Stephen K. Hayes| work = Google Books | accessdate = 2012-11-14}}</ref> * ''Kamui'': Series of five novels by [[Tetsu Yano]], later adapted in manga, anime and live-action formats * ''[[Ninja (comic book)|Ninja]]'' ([[Serbian language|Serbian]]: ''Ninđa'' or ''Nindža'') was a series of more than 150 [[Pulp magazine|pulp novels]], mostly written by Brana Nikolić alias Derek Finegan, published in [[Yugoslavia]] 1983-1998 * ''Ninja's Revenge'' and ''The Bamboo Bloodbath'' by [[Piers Anthony]]<ref name=dw/> * ''Mirror Friend, Mirror Foe'': Novel by [[Robert Asprin]] and [[George Takei]], featuring a future ninja clan member * ''[[The Ninja (book)|The Ninja]]'': [[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]] by [[Eric Van Lustbader]] featuring a half-Japanese, half-white character who received ninjutsu training in his youth; followed by ''The Miko'', ''White Ninja'', ''The Kaisho'', ''Floating City'' and ''Second Skin'' * ''The Ninja Murders'': Historical novel by Andrew B. Suhrer * ''[[Ninja Slayer]]'': Series of Japanese cyberpunk novels by "Bradley Bond",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ninjaslayer.jp/index.html|title=ニンジャスレイヤー書籍公式サイト|publisher=Ninjaslayer.jp|date=|accessdate=2013-11-03|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012142919/http://ninjaslayer.jp/index.html|archivedate=2013-10-12|df=}}</ref> later adapted into manga and anime series * ''Not for Glory'': [[Space opera]] novel by [[Joel Rosenberg (science fiction author)|Joel Rosenberg]] about a mercenary Jewish-Japanese tribe which practices ninjutsu * ''[[Sanada Ten Braves|Sanada Ten Braves (Sanada Jūyūshi)]]:'' [[Meiji period|Meiji]] legend, first published in novel form in 1912 during the [[Taishō period]] * ''[[Shinobi no Mono]]'': Series of novels by [[Tomoyoshi Murayama]] about the life of Ishikawa Goemon. During the 1960s, it was adapted into a series of films about Goemon and other historical ninja. * ''[[Tales of the Otori]]'': The Tribe consists of five ninja families with powers. * ''Tsuma-wa, Kunoichi'': Historical novel<ref>{{cite web|author=原作：風野真知雄 |url=http://www.kadokawa.co.jp/product/321211000202/ |title=株式会社KADOKAWAオフィシャルサイト｜妻は、くノ一 |publisher=Kadokawa.co.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-06}}</ref>
Ninja have minor roles in ''[[Shōgun (novel)|Shōgun]]'', ''[[Thief of Time]]'', ''[[Vineland]]''<ref>{{cite web|last=Beckett | first=Andy |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2010/jul/31/thomas-pynchon-vineland-rereading |title=Rereading: Vineland by Thomas Pynchon &#124; Books |publisher=The Guardian |date=2012-11-09 |accessdate=2012-11-14}}</ref> and the ''[[Young Samurai]]'' series.
===={{anchor|In non-Japanese comics}}Non-Japanese comics==== [[File:Cosplayer of Psylocke 2012-04-24.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Scantily-clad young woman with a sword|[[Psylocke]] cosplayer, 2014]] In the [[Marvel Universe]], ninjas have been heroes and villains. Examples include [[Spider-Man]]'s foe White Ninja, [[X-Men]] members [[Psylocke]], [[Revanche (Marvel Comics)|Revanche]] and supporting character [[Yukio (comics)|Yukio]], [[Ghost Rider]]'s foes [[Deathwatch (comics)|Deathwatch]] and Death Ninja, [[Wolverine (character)|Wolverine]]'s mentor [[Ogun (Marvel Comics)|Ogun]], [[Hawkeye (comics)|Hawkeye]] (as Ninja Ronin), the [[Punisher]]'s friend Katherine Yakamoto (from [[Shadowmasters]]), and [[Pacific Overlords]] operative Kuroko (Aya Komatsu). In the ''[[Marvel Mangaverse]]'', Spider-Man is the last member of a ninja clan. A sinister ninja cult, [[The Hand (comics)|the Hand]], appears in ''[[X-Men]]'' and ''[[Daredevil (Marvel Comics series)|Daredevil]]''. The cult and its associates were responsible for the martial training of Psylocke, [[Elektra (comics)|Elektra]], Daredevil, [[Black Tarantula]], [[Kitty Pryde]], [[Lady Bullseye]] and Wolverine. The Hand's heroic counterpart is [[The Chaste]], which struggles with its Korean offshoot the True Believers (including Dragonfly Meiko Yin).
Characters with mystical, superhuman martial-arts abilities attributed to ninja appear in the [[DC Universe]]. Bruce Wayne received ninja training prior to becoming Batman. Another character portrayed similarly to a ninja is master martial artist and assassin [[Lady Shiva]]; Shiva killed [[Armless Master]], who trained [[Catwoman]] and [[Hellhound]]. One alternative-universe comic substitutes Batman with a Japanese female ninja named Komori (Bat).<ref>''Justice League of America: Shogun of Steel'' (Elseworlds, 2002).</ref> An [[Alternative versions of Robin|alternative version of Robin]], Tengu, was raised by Cat-Ninja (Catwoman) in feudal Japan. DC's [[The New 52]] introduced Kunoichi, a member of the [[Blackhawks (DC Comics)|Blackhawks]].
In the ''[[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles]]'' (TMNT) series, the [[List of Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles characters|main characters and many of their friends and foes]] are ninja, mainly from the [[Foot Clan]] (a pastiche of Marvel's group, the Hand): [[Donatello (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Donatello]], [[Leonardo (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Leonardo]], [[Michelangelo (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Michelangelo]], [[Raphael (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Raphael]], [[Splinter (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Splinter]], [[Shredder (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Shredder]] and [[Karai (character)|Karai]].
The comic version of ''[[G.I. Joe]]'' has featured more ninja than the cartoon series. Story arcs involved [[Scarlett (G.I. Joe)|Scarlett]], [[Snake Eyes (G.I. Joe)|Snake Eyes]], [[Storm Shadow (G.I. Joe)|Storm Shadow]], [[Jinx (G.I. Joe)|Jinx]], [[Kamakura (G.I. Joe)|Kamakura]], [[Firefly (G.I. Joe)|Firefly]] and the [[Arashikage]] ninja clan, an extended family of ninja characters. [[Cobra Commander]]'s son, [[Billy Kessler]], and the shape-shifter [[Zartan]] also received ninja training from the Arashikage clan and their associates.
Other ninja-themed comics include: * ''[[Biotrog]]'' * ''[[Blade for Barter]]'' * ''[[Cowboy Ninja Viking]]'' * ''Half Past Danger''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2013/05/07/half-past-danger-comic-book-series/2140391/|title='Half Past Danger' is adventure time for Stephen Mooney|author=Brian Truitt|date=7 May 2013|publisher=Usatoday.com|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> * ''[[Jetta: Tales of the Toshigawa]]'' * ''[[Naruto]]'' * ''[[Kabuki (comics)|Kabuki]]'': Series about a member of a government-backed circle of masked, costumed female assassins in near-future Japan * ''Kyoteru'' * ''[[Mail Order Ninja]]'' * ''[[Mortal Kombat comic books|Mortal Kombat]]'': Series based on the video-game series of the same name with [[Jade (Mortal Kombat)|Jade]], [[Kitana (Mortal Kombat)|Kitana]], [[Mileena]], [[Reptile (Mortal Kombat)|Reptile]], [[Scorpion (Mortal Kombat)|Scorpion]] and [[Sub-Zero (Mortal Kombat)|Sub-Zero]] * ''[[Ninja (comic book)|Ninja]]'': Series published from 1986 to 1989 in 40 episodes in [[Yugoslavia]] * ''[[Ninja Boy]]'' * ''[[Ninja Funnies]]'' * ''[[Ninja High School]]'': Ninja-themed, comedy series * ''[[Ninjak]]'' * ''[[Nth Man: The Ultimate Ninja]]'': An American ninja during World War III * ''[[Pirates Vs. Ninjas]]'' * ''Samurai's Blood''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gotham-news.com/news/2011/10/20/erics-image-comics-review-samurais-blood-5|title=Eric's Image Comics Review: SAMURAI'S BLOOD #5|publisher=Gotham-news.com|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> * ''[[Shi (comics)|Shi]]'': Series about a modern war between descendants of medieval Japanese warrior monks * ''[[Sin City]]'': ''[[Hardboiled|Noir]]'' series with [[Miho (Sin City)|Miho]] * ''Teenage Mutant Ninja Turkeys'': [[Dean Rankine]]'s parody of ''Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles'' for ''[[The Beano]]'' * ''Whisper'': Series by [[Steven Grant]] about a modern female ninja.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vintageninja.net/?p=2480 |title=WHISPER covers |publisher=Vintage Ninja |date=2012-05-04 |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Zen the Intergalactic Ninja]]''
Short-lived titles include ''Codename: Ninja''{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} and ''Zombee''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.comics.ign.com/articles/741/741394p1.html |title=Zombee Review&nbsp;– Comics Review at IGN |publisher=Uk.comics.ign.com |date=2006-10-24 |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> The ''[[Amelia Rules!]]'' series included ''A Very Ninja Christmas''.
Ninja have supporting roles in ''[[Karate Kommandos]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.misterkitty.org/extras/stupidcovers/stupidcomics102.html |title=Stupid Comics |publisher=Misterkitty.org |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> ''[[Lucha Libre (comics)|Lucha Libre]]'' ''[[Les Naufragés d'Ythaq]]'',{{cn|date=September 2018}} ''[[Masters of the Universe]]'' (Ninjor),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.he-man.org/collecting/toy.php?id=1241 |title=Ninjor |publisher=He-Man.org |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> ''[[Rebirth (manhwa)|Rebirth]]'' (the hero's ally, Eiji Inaba),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animevice.com/eiji-inaba/18-29679/ |title=Eiji Inaba (anime/manga character) |publisher=Animevice.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130926073853/http://www.animevice.com/eiji-inaba/18-29679/ |archivedate=September 26, 2013 }}</ref> ''[[Sam Noir]]'' (villains),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thrillingdetective.com/eyes/sam_noir.html#special |title=Sam Noir |publisher=Thrillingdetective.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> ''[[Scott Pilgrim]]'' (Roxanne "Roxie" Richter), ''[[Spike: Shadow Puppets]]'', ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog (comic book)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' (Uma Arachnis and the Arachne), ''[[The Order of the Stick]]'' (Therkla and others), ''[[The Tick]]'' (Oedipus),<ref>{{cite web|author=Michael R. Legg |url=http://www.thetick.ws/comheroes.html |title=The Tick comics gallery of superheroes |publisher=Thetick.ws |date=1998-09-27 |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> and ''[[Usagi Yojimbo]]'' (ninja of the Neko,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usagiyojimbo.com/other/characters/neko-ninja.html |title=Neko Ninja&nbsp;– Usagi Yojimbo Dojo |publisher=Usagiyojimbo.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> Mogura and Komori clans, including Kashira Chizu).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usagiyojimbo.com/characters/chizu.html |title=Usagi Yojimbo Dojo&nbsp;– Kashira Chizu |publisher=Usagiyojimbo.com |date=2004-01-13 |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref>
==={{anchor|In music}}Music=== Several musicians and bands have the word "ninja" in their names: *[[Watkin Tudor Jones|Ninja]] *Ninja Crew<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2011/05/the-50-best-new-orleans-rap-songs/ninja-crew-we-destroy-1986 |title=#43. Ninja Crew "We Destroy" (1986)&nbsp;— The 50 Best New Orleans Rap Songs |publisher=Complex |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> *[[Ninja High School (band)|Ninja High School]] *[[Ninja Sarasalo]] *[[Ninjaman]] *[[Shinobi Ninja]] *[[Twelve Foot Ninja]] *[[Vanilla Ninja]] *[[Ninja Sex Party]]
A number of titles include "ninja" or "kunoichi": *''[[Club Ninja]]'' (album by [[Blue Öyster Cult]]) *''Camouflage Ninjas'' (single by [[Killarmy]]) *''DANGEROUS Kunoichi'' (mini-album by Akashic)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.akasick.info/discography/913/ |title=DANGEROUS くノ一 &#124; アカシック |publisher=Akasick.info |date=2015-05-11 |accessdate=2015-11-06}}</ref> *''[[Deadly Lethal Ninja Assassin]]'' (single by [[In Nothing We Trust]]) *''[[Ninja (album)|Ninja]]'' (debut album by [[Christina Aguilar]]) *''Ninja Jane'' (album by [[Zola Turn]]) *''[[NINJA 2009 Tour Sampler|NINJA]]'' (collaborative album by [[Nine Inch Nails]], [[Jane's Addiction]] and [[Street Sweeper Social Club]]) *''[[Shinobi vs. Dragon Ninja]]'' (debut single of [[Lostprophets]]) *''Ninja'' (a single by [[Skindred]])
Songs with "ninja" in their titles include "Deadly Lethal Ninja Assassin" by [[Reuben (band)|Reuben]] (on ''[[We Should Have Gone To University]]''), "Hoodie Ninja" by [[mc chris]] (on ''[[mc chris is dead]]''), "Imaginary Ninjas" by [[Vince Dicola]] (on ''[[Falling off a Clef (album)|Falling off a Clef]]''), "[[Inner Ninja]]" by [[Classified (rapper)|Classified]] (on ''[[Classified (Classified album)|Classified]]''),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7fDuNuFNG38|title=Classified feat. David Myles - Inner Ninja [Official Video]|work=YouTube|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> "Ninja Goon" by [[Gruvis Malt]] (on ''[[Sound Soldiers]]''), "Ninja Hi-skool" by [[Bis (band)|Bis]] (on ''[[Play Some Real Songs: the Live Album]]''), "We Are Ninja" by [[Frank Chickens]] (on ''[[We Are Frank Chickens]]''), "Ninja Highschooool" by [[Peelander-Z]] (on ''[[P-Pop-High School]]''), "Ninja Rap" by [[Vanilla Ice]] (on the [[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles II The Secret of the Ooze: The Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|''TMNT II'' soundtrack]]), "Ninja Step" by [[RZA]] (on the ''[[Ghost Dog: The Way of the Samurai (soundtrack)|Ghost Dog: The Way of the Samurai]]'' soundtrack), "Ninja Quiet" by [[Marco Beltrami]] (on ''[[World War Z: Music from the Motion Picture]]''), "Supa Ninjaz" by [[Method Man]] (on ''[[The Pillage]]''), and "This Secret Ninja" by [[AFI (band)|AFI]] (on ''[[Very Proud of Ya]]''). [[Ninja Tune]] is a London-based independent record label. Built by Ninjas is a music video production group formed by [[Jaret Reddick]] and Heath Balderston.<ref name="Ninjas3">{{cite web|title=BOWLING FOR SOUP|url=http://www.rockonmagazine.com/2011/06/bowling-for-soup.html?sms_ss=twitter&at_xt=4de69604a19ba4ae,0|publisher=rockonmagazine.com|accessdate=2 June 2011|date=1 June 2011}}</ref><ref name="Ninjas">{{cite web|title=BUILT BY NINJAS >> ABOUT|url=http://builtbyninjas.com/about|publisher=builtbyninjas.com|accessdate=28 May 2011|year=2011}}</ref> Fans of the rap group [[Insane Clown Posse]], known as [[juggalo]]s, sometimes refer to themselves as "ninja".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/read/land-of-juggalos-v14n10|title=In the Land of the Juggalos|work=VICE|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref>
Ninja appear in the music video for the [[Presidents of the United States of America (band)|Presidents of the United States of America]]'s song, "[[Peaches (The Presidents of the United States of America song)|Peaches]]". [[Cheryl Cole]] dressed as a female ninja and performed with a group of similarly-dressed dancers in the TV special, ''[[Cheryl Cole's Night In]]''.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sophie Freeman |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-1234671/Cheryl-Cole-prepares-Saturdays-X-Factor-fight-Ninja-routine-TV-special.html |title=Cheryl Cole prepares for Saturday's X Factor fight with Ninja routine on TV special &#124; Mail Online |publisher=Dailymail.co.uk |date= 2009-12-10|accessdate=2010-06-30 | location=London}}</ref> Members of [[Momoiro Clover Z]] dressed as ninja for the music video for "[[D' no Junjō]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UVKHgXoqyuc|title=D'の純情／ももいろクローバーZ Full ver.（D'NO JUNJOU／MOMOIRO CLOVER Z）|work=YouTube|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> [[Rika Adachi]] performed in a music video based on a song from ''Naruto''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mdpr.jp/news/detail/1497501 |title=足立梨花、初の"くノ一"姿を披露「戦ってます！」 - モデルプレス |publisher=Mdpr.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-06}}</ref>
===Other=== According to [[Indeed.com]], there was a 7,000-percent increase in the number of job listings with the word "ninja" from 2006 to 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=McMillan |first=Robert |url=https://www.wired.com/wiredenterprise/2012/05/ninja_job/ |title=Looking for a Coding Job? Better a Ninja Than a Brogrammer |publisher=Wired|date=2012-05-21 |accessdate=2013-08-05}}</ref> A former Russian soldier who committed robberies in Italy in black attire and a bow was called a "Russian ninja" by the BBC.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fraser |first=Christian |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6746051.stm |title=Europe &#124; Russian 'ninja' arrested in Italy |publisher=BBC News |date=2007-06-12 |accessdate=2010-06-30}}</ref> The video-game series ''[[Tenchu]]'' was adapted for the Japanese stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.ameba.jp/20140508-555/ |title=舞台版「天誅」でござる！ 元新体操選手の江田結香が魅せる くノ一アクション - Ameba News [アメーバニュース&#93; |language=ja |publisher=News.ameba.jp |date=1994-12-01 |accessdate=2015-11-06}}</ref> In 2006, Miss Japan [[Kurara Chibana]] appeared in a ninja-samurai costume for the [[Miss Universe]] competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.3yen.com/2006-07-19/miss-universe-in-ninja-high-heels/ |title=News on Japan&nbsp;– Miss Universe in ninja high heels |publisher=News.3yen.com |date=2006-07-19 |accessdate=2010-06-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://girls.gunaxin.com/14-incredibly-hot-japanese-women-youve-never-heard-of/28188 |title=14 Incredibly Hot Japanese Women (You've Never Heard Of) &#124; Gunaxin Girls |publisher=Girls.gunaxin.com |date=2009-09-10 |accessdate=2013-08-05}}</ref> Goth Ninja, a type of Japanese street fashion, became popular in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last=Betts |first=Kate |url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1945379_1944764_1944762,00.html#ixzz0psA7ImHB |title=Goth Ninja&nbsp;– The Top 10 Everything of 2009 |work=[[TIME (magazine)|TIME]] |date=2009-12-08 |accessdate=2010-06-30}}</ref>
